Diagnosis.
Body form in lateral view weakly dorsoventrally convex; elytral glabrous region of male (
Figs. 2F
, 
10A
) cordiform, along suture extending ca. 7/9 length of elytra, laterally expanded in anterior 2/3 to considerably wider than pronotal glabrous region, posterior 1/3 strongly acuminate with weakly rounded margins; female elytral glabrous region similar to male (
Figs. 3F
, 
10E
), except with weaker apical acumination; elytral apex of both sexes similar, obliquely truncate without apicolateral sinuation, epipleural angle distinct, weakly rounded; male protibia (
Fig. 4F
) cleaver shaped, constricted in basal 2/5, protibial apex truncate with prominent distolateral angle; male protarsus (
Fig. 4F
) ca. 1/2 length of protibia, protarsomeres width gradually decreasing apically; mesoventrite without medial pit; aedeagus (
Fig. 10B
) with median lobe evenly tapered, apex constricted in lateral view (
Fig. 10C
); female reproductive tract (
Fig. 10G
) without additional sclerite between gonocoxae (
Fig. 10F
), fertilization duct as in 
Fig. 10H
.

Male genitalia. Aedeagus (
Fig. 10B
) with median lobe ca. 4/5 length of parameres, evenly tapered, apex in lateral view noticeably constricted (
Fig. 10C
), operculum as in 
Fig. 10D
; parameres narrowly rounded apically (
Fig. 10B
).

Female genitalia. Reproductive tract with large sac-like spermatheca (
Fig. 10G
); fertilization duct sclerotized, highly convoluted (
Fig. 10H
); small sclerite present posterior to oviduct; additional round sclerite between gonocoxae absent; gonocoxae narrow, apically broadly rounded, laterally with nearly straight margins (
Fig. 10F
).

Distribution.
This species is currently known from Phu Hin Rongkla National Park and Phu Kradueng National Park (
Fig. 13D
) and Phu Rua National Park, which are all within the 
Phetchabun
mountain range (
Fig. 14B
); this is an area exhibiting high levels of endemism among aquatic insects (
Sites & Polhemus 2001
; 
Vitheepradit & Sites 2007
), including whirligig beetles (

Gustafson 
et al
. 2016

). Additonally, this species has been collected from Doi Phu Ka National Park which is located within the 
Luang Prabang
mountain range (
Fig 14B
).
